> she caught for a fraction of a second and died... kept doing this, and on about
> the fourth time there was a puff of fuel-air and a little bit of flame out one
> of the intake hoses (the hoses that seal the connection between the intake air
> distributor and the intake headers - the two deals on either side that the
> injectors are attached to)... anyway, it only happened on the left side...
> >
> > so i have rebuilt heads from a shop here in seattle (northwest connecting
> rods)... i noticed that they pink their valve seats in, if that makes a
> difference here... the reason i mention valves is because as i've thought this
> problem through this evening on my way up to the san juans in Molly, my backup
> 76 celica that i bought for two hundred bucks when i tore the van engine apart
> and who has run perfectly fine for five months even though she backfires,
> diesels, and can't maintain an idle in the cold (you should see the nightmare
> that the last mechanic to work on her made of the carb linkages and lines - yet
> there's nothing quite like the 20R enging) - i've been thinking that the only
> reason you might get pressure back into the intake headers is if the intake
> valves are not sealing all the way when the piston is on the upswing, so i must
> be getting some blowby into the intake system... but i did set the valves, and
> i'm fairly certain i did it correctly (i say fairly only beca!
> > use i am always second guessing myself)...
> >
> > anyway, if anyone might have an idea of what might be wrong (incidentally,
> though i continued trying to start her she didn't flame out the headers again
> but she still pushes fuel air out cause there is a bit of moisture coming out
> those hoses) i'd love to hear some advice... a couple other things that might
> help the diagnosis: i put a clamp on the boot (that's probably a better word to
> use than hose) where it had pushed out before and that stopped it on that side,
> but only that side... i could conceivably clamp all 8 points on those boots
> (leading to both heads that is) but the more i think about it the more i'm
> worried about the fact that pressure is coming up from the heads... one thing to
> note on the side that it is pushing out the two tubes on the header are slightly
> cocked to the ports on the air ditributor so the boots aren't quite straight,
> thus might not make a terrific seal... also, with further attempts at starting
> she would start and run for a half second (but lon!
> > ger than at first) and then cough to a stop... usually it was when she coughed
> to a stop that i'd hear air being forced out of those boots... oh yeah and my
> timing might not be right on (4 atdc that is) as i didn't mark the distributor
